    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>YOUTH DRUG USE</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Steve Strunsky</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Strunsky, Steve</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Partnership for Drug Free New Jersey survey finds decline in number of seventh and eighth graders smoking marjiuana and drinking since 1995 (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Fewer seventh and eighth graders are smoking marijuana and drinking, a report by the Partnership for a Drug Free New Jersey found last week. In its survey, 9 percent of students reported smoking marijuana within the past year, down from 13 percent in 1995, and drinking fell from 49 to 41 percent over the same period. The survey also found that students who talk to parents daily are less likely to drink or take drugs.</p>
        <p>Steve Strunsky</p>
      </block>
